snippet.textDisplay: Imagine someone like I dunno, say any major snack company, decides to simply make and sell prepacked olives with a long shelf life to pubs. With their scale of production, distribution and budget for advertising they would cripple her company within a month. It's not like the pole and shape of the package are a unique selling point that people would come back for more rather than try a competitor. She would have been better off marketing the product as something like 'Auntie Jealpoe's Organic Italian Family Recipe Whole Olives' and should have had a nice big sign with a smiling Italian grandmother giving some olives to a smiling bright eyed little child in a garden on a hot summers day. Then at least people would want to try them and have something to talk about. Those olive containers were about as drab as the person trying to pitch them, but in no way as offensive as her. Hilarious how she shat on the entire Spanish people because of either a bad supplier or miscommunication.

snippet.textDisplay:
She has found a niche and her trouble is each and every person she pitches can see it so they are potential competitors so she's got a sensitivity about that. She answered their question but she told them in a roundabout manner as regards the turnover, (one a day so 20p profit a day for 2 and a half years) which is impossible for any product there would be more average sales statistically. Is it that meat pie which troubles her or was that damage limitation as regards tax (paid 40% on 20p per day tax for 2 and a half years l guess? ) I assume she couldn't stomach to speak that Truth 🤔 which went part and parcel in failing to get a [15%] partnership.
Further, she's left herself open to others to guess at the deeper meaning of this cageyness whether there are other problems not only of a tax nature that she"s neglected. She's definitely queered her pitch with some argument or other with her Spanish contacts. Brexit is also a possible problem for Spanish suppliers so maybe the argument was about that. 🤔 It was also definitely about putting [sulphur] preservative in the product normally hidden with the addition of vinegar the indigestion (poisoning) pains from preservatives are numbed by alcohol since their target market is the frequenter of the Great British pub. (Perhaps preserve in brine or oil?)
One part of me wants to like her if there was some argument concerming preservatives which means there is a moral concern towards her customers. But the other part, that she discriminates her would-be suppliers (biting the potential hands that feed her.) Of course she could grow the product in glass houses herself or source in Turkey or Greece (Kalamata 🤔)
Deep down l believe she didn't want investment and this was nothing more than a free commercial paid for by the Great British licence payer.
So far as Brexit is concerned she's a metaphor for those that are pro.
I however can guarantee you will see these olives around pubs on the NTD future. ("Not too distant.") 🤔
